<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900403-0085</DOCNO><DOCID>900403-0085.</DOCID><HL>   REVIEW andamp; OUTLOOK (Editorial) -- Asides:   Ancient History</HL><DATE>04/03/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A20</SO><GV>CONGRESS (CNG)</GV><LP>   Bad news for Washington, if not the Republic: There'sevidence that for most American kids, Washington is history.A report just out by the National Assessment of EducationalProgress says only about one-third of polled eighth gradersknow that Congress makes the laws or could identify thepresidential veto. About half know that the U.S. is arepresentative democracy or understand the separation ofpowers. Still, there may be reasons for these results.   Maybe they'd be better able to recognize their governmentif someone asked them what a $500 billion omnibusappropriation bill was. Or a continuing resolution. Most kidsin grade school probably think local judges make the nation'slaws. How is a 13-year-old supposed to know what apresidential veto is if nobody's spotted more than one or twosince 1974? As to the U.S. being a representative democracy,is this question related to the 99% re-election rate in theHouse of Representatives? The reason some of their parentsdon't vote is that increasing numbers of Members have noopponent in the general election.</LP><TEXT>   We do wonder about one thing, though. If 33% know thatCongress makes laws, what does the other 66% think Congressdoes?</TEXT></DOC>